Your two pods are on different worker nodes (worker3 vs worker1), and the ~0.48s skew is consistent across all three measurements. This is node clock drift, not a pod-level problem. Pods inherit the kernel clock of their host node, so the fix is at the node/host layer.

**Diagnose which nodes are off:**

```bash
# Check time sync status on each node
oc debug node/worker3.dev.sbiepay.sbi -- chroot /host timedatectl status
oc debug node/worker1.dev.sbiepay.sbi -- chroot /host timedatectl status

# Or directly via chronyd
oc debug node/worker1.dev.sbiepay.sbi -- chroot /host chronyc tracking
oc debug node/worker1.dev.sbiepay.sbi -- chroot /host chronyc sources -v
```

Look for `System clock synchronized: yes` and a small `Last offset` / `RMS offset` in `chronyc tracking`. A ~480ms offset means chrony either isn't reaching its source or isn't running on one of the nodes.

**Most likely cause in an air-gapped env:** the nodes can't reach an NTP server. Public pool servers (rhel.pool.ntp.org, etc.) are unreachable, so chrony falls back to free-running local clocks that drift apart. You need an internal NTP/PTP source.

**Fix — point chrony at your internal time source via MachineConfig** (this is the supported OpenShift method, survives reboots/scaling):

```bash
# Build the chrony.conf
cat > chrony.conf << 'EOF'
server <your-internal-ntp-ip> iburst
driftfile /var/lib/chrony/drift
makestep 1.0 3
rtcsync
EOF

# Base64 encode it
BASE64=$(base64 -w0 chrony.conf)
```

Then create a MachineConfig for the worker pool:

```yaml
apiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1
kind: MachineConfig
metadata:
  labels:
    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker
  name: 99-worker-chrony-conf
spec:
  config:
    ignition:
      version: 3.2.0
    storage:
      files:
      - contents:
          source: data:text/plain;charset=utf-8;base64,<BASE64_STRING>
        mode: 420
        overwrite: true
        path: /etc/chrony.conf
```

```bash
oc apply -f 99-worker-chrony-conf.yaml
```

MCO will roll the worker pool one node at a time (drains/reboots). Watch with `oc get mcp worker -w`.

**Verify after rollout:**

```bash
oc debug node/worker1.dev.sbiepay.sbi -- chroot /host chronyc tracking
# Re-run your two-pod comparison; offsets should be sub-millisecond to low-ms
```

One thing to confirm first: do all your air-gapped nodes already have a reachable internal NTP server, or does one need to be stood up? If there's no internal time source at all, that's the root cause and the MachineConfig needs a valid `server` IP to point at. If you tell me your time-source setup I can tailor the config.
